# Going Balls — AI Assistant Rules
# Loaded automatically for all Codebuff sessions on this project.

## CRITICAL: Ask Before Delete
- NEVER delete any file without first asking the user to confirm.
- Use the ask_user tool to present what would be deleted and why.
- This applies to: source files, asset files, configuration, documentation, and generated files.
- Exception: temporary build artifacts in .gitignore'd directories (e.g., node_modules/, dist/) may be cleaned without asking — but still confirm with the user before doing so.

## CRITICAL: Backup Before Destructive Changes
- Before making any change that removes or substantially rewrites functionality:
  1. Create a backup copy of the affected file(s) with a `.bak` extension or timestamp suffix.
  2. Inform the user where the backup is stored.
  Example: `cp src/file.js src/file.js.bak-2026-06-21`
- "Substantially rewriting" includes: refactoring methods out of a class, restructuring module exports, replacing algorithm logic.
- Simple additions (new CSS rules, new functions, property additions) do not require backup.
- The user can always restore from git history, but a local backup provides an immediate safety net.

## Asset Management
- All image files (.png, .jpg, .webp, .gif) live under `assets/image/`.
- All 3D model files (.glb, .gltf, .bin) live under `assets/model/`.
- All audio files (.mp3) live under `assets/sfx/`.
- All font files (.ttf, .woff, .woff2) live under `assets/font/`.
- When adding new assets, place them in the correct subdirectory.
- When referencing assets in code, use the full `assets/<type>/<filename>` path.

## Code Architecture
- `main.js` (root) — thin DI bootstrap shell. No business logic. Wires modules together.
- `engine/scene.js` — Three.js scene, camera, renderer, materials, sky, textures.
- `src/physics.js` — cannon-es world, ball body, forces, particles.
- `src/levelgen.js` — procedural level generation and obstacle builders.
- `src/ui.js` — DOM UI, modals, shop, leaderboard, game state.
- `src/audio.js` — audio init, music toggle, SFX pool.
- `src/persistence.js` — localStorage save/load, configs, RNG.
- `src/networking.js` — WebsimSocket init, loading manager, error handlers.
- `src/rendering.js` — animation loop, camera follow, particle updates.
- `src/ball_db.js` — canonical ball skin data (single source of truth).
- `src/ball_index_ui.js` — ball index UI rendering.
- `src/notification_manager.js` — toast notification pool and rate limiter.
- `index.html` — app shell, CSS, import map, UI skeleton.

## Import Conventions
- Root `main.js` imports modules with `./src/<module>.js` or `./engine/<module>.js`.
- Modules inside `src/` that need `engine/scene.js` use `../engine/scene.js`.
- Modules inside `src/` reference each other with `./<module>.js`.
- Use ES module `import`/`export` exclusively — no CommonJS.

## Code Style
- Mimic existing patterns: try/catch wrapping, defensive null checks, early returns.
- Use `game` as the first parameter for module functions (DI pattern).
- Shared materials, configs, and state go on the `game` object.
- Document each module with a JSDoc-style header comment listing exports.

## Unused Imports Rule
- NEVER delete an unused import/variable just to silence a lint warning.
- Instead, find a way to USE it that adds real user value — validation, logging, feature hooks, error context, undo tracking, etc.
- If an import is truly dead (no future use at all), prefix with `_` only as a last resort.
- The goal is: every import earns its place by solving a real problem or enabling a real feature.

## Before Committing Changes
- Run the code-reviewer-deepseek agent on significant changes.
- Fix all issues found before marking work as complete.
- Verify import paths are correct across all changed files.
